  "prompt": "Why do we not feel like sleeping but when we're sleeping we don't feel like waking?",
  "response": "This phenomenon is related to the complex interaction of various biological processes and neurotransmitters in our brain. Here are some key reasons:\n\n1. Circadian Rhythm\n- Our internal biological clock regulates sleep-wake cycles\n- Controlled by the suprachiasmatic nucleus in the brain\n- Influenced by light exposure and hormones like melatonin\n\n2. Sleep Inertia\n- When sleeping, our brain is in a different state of consciousness\n- Transition from sleep to wakefulness involves grogginess and resistance\n- Hormones like adenosine and melatonin make us feel sleepy and want to continue sleeping\n\n3. Sleep Stages\n- During deep sleep (slow-wave sleep), we're less responsive to external stimuli\n- The brain is less active and more resistant to waking up\n\n4. Psychological Factors\n- When awake, we're stimulated by activities, thoughts, and environment\n- At night, we feel alert due to ongoing mental and physical engagement\n\n5. Hormonal Changes\n- Cortisol (stress hormone) is low during night\n- Melatonin increases, promoting sleepiness\n- Upon waking, cortisol rises, promoting alertness\n\nThese complex interactions explain why we often feel differently about sleeping when awake versus when actually sleeping.",
